The Times website, which broke the story, crashed after

00:06:09.222 --> 00:06:12.512
publishing the story with the headline “Bring Me Home”.

00:06:14.022 --> 00:06:17.312
And then something very strange happened.

00:06:18.602 --> 00:06:23.672
The day after the news of her discovery was published, the British Home Secretary,

00:06:23.972 --> 00:06:29.592
a top member of the government, revoked her citizenship, he said that she was

00:06:29.602 --> 00:06:35.012
no longer a British citizen, and therefore she had no right to come to Britain.

00:06:36.552 --> 00:06:44.392
Suddenly this 19-year-old woman was stateless, she had no passport, no country to call her own.

00:06:45.842 --> 00:06:50.322
Now, for the absence of doubt, and putting aside whatever you might

00:06:50.322 --> 00:06:54.962
think about her beliefs and actions, Shamima Begum was legally British.

00:06:55.542 --> 00:06:58.752
She was born in London, her father was from Bangladesh

00:06:58.822 --> 00:07:02.062
but he had something called “indefinite leave to remain”.

00:07:03.222 --> 00:07:07.832
This meant that Begum was legally a British citizen, just like

00:07:07.862 --> 00:07:12.532
any other, but she found her citizenship stripped from her.

00:07:13.942 --> 00:07:20.342
And again, on a legal basis, the British state does have the right to remove someone’s citizenship.

00:07:21.402 --> 00:07:26.162
In this case, the Home Secretary did it on the grounds of national security.

00:07:27.352 --> 00:07:31.742
He said that she had done something so terrible, she had pledged her

00:07:31.772 --> 00:07:37.362
allegiance to a regime that was so abhorrent, with beliefs so contrary to

00:07:37.392 --> 00:07:42.202
British beliefs, that she had forfeited her right to British citizenship.

00:07:42.902 --> 00:07:46.822
She was not welcome in Britain, the Home Secretary said, it

00:07:46.822 --> 00:07:50.772
was no longer her home, and he would not let her return here.

00:07:52.182 --> 00:07:57.802
This was in February of 2019, and to this day, as of the time of

00:07:57.802 --> 00:08:02.232
recording this episode at least, the situation has not changed; she

00:08:02.232 --> 00:08:06.962
is still in a Syrian refugee camp, without a state to call her own.

00:08:08.522 --> 00:08:15.545
To some, this is fair and just; nationhood and citizenship are things that a country

00:08:15.545 --> 00:08:21.851
can give out and take away, and in the case of Shamima Begum, she made her choice,

00:08:22.191 --> 00:08:27.921
she knew what she was doing, and she pledged loyalty to a state so horrific that

00:08:27.941 --> 00:08:32.471
it is perfectly justified that she forfeited her right to call herself British.

00:08:34.001 --> 00:08:39.601
To others, it is a deeply unfair decision against a young woman who didn’t fully

00:08:39.631 --> 00:08:45.761
understand what she was doing, who made a teenage mistake and has already suffered greatly.

00:08:46.711 --> 00:08:53.491
Removing her citizenship is not only unnecessary and overly punitive, it is also illegal.

00:08:54.681 --> 00:09:00.231
So, to begin with, let’s explore the first position, the position of the British

00:09:00.231 --> 00:09:05.861
government, that Shamima Begum has forfeited her right to British citizenship.

00:09:07.341 --> 00:09:11.051
As you heard, the day after her first interview with the BBC, the

00:09:11.051 --> 00:09:15.561
Home Secretary publicly declared that her passport had been revoked.

00:09:16.831 --> 00:09:21.111
The British government's position hinges on a few key points.

00:09:22.571 --> 00:09:25.981
Firstly, there is the argument of national security.

00:09:27.237 --> 00:09:31.842
The Home Secretary, in revoking Shamima Begum's citizenship, implied

00:09:31.972 --> 00:09:36.132
that her return could pose a threat to the security of the country.

00:09:37.202 --> 00:09:41.422
She had been in ISIS for 4 years, with reports about her

00:09:41.452 --> 00:09:44.552
being actively involved in the day-to-day operations.

00:09:46.072 --> 00:09:49.002
She would later deny that she was anything more than a housewife,

00:09:49.372 --> 00:09:52.792
but not everyone was buying this, not everyone believed her.

00:09:54.172 --> 00:09:59.102
What’s more, she only left the caliphate after the Islamic State started

00:09:59.102 --> 00:10:04.262
to fall, and her first interviews seemed to show that she still believed

00:10:04.262 --> 00:10:09.762
in ISIS and showed no remorse for its actions or her actions by joining it.

00:10:11.242 --> 00:10:15.772
If she were to return to the UK, so the argument goes, it’s highly

00:10:15.772 --> 00:10:20.542
probable that she would radicalise others, help terrorist networks in the

00:10:20.542 --> 00:10:25.522
country, or at least be held up as a poster girl for Islamic terrorism.

00:10:27.112 --> 00:10:29.342
Secondly, there's the legal aspect.

00:10:30.442 --> 00:10:35.002
You might think that it is illegal for a country to simply decide that one of its

00:10:35.002 --> 00:10:41.642
citizens is no longer a citizen, and it is in most cases, but there are some exceptions.

00:10:43.072 --> 00:10:50.242
One of these is if the person concerned won’t be stateless, so if they have another nationality.

00:10:51.792 --> 00:10:56.822
In Begum's case, it was initially argued that she could claim citizenship

00:10:57.042 --> 00:11:01.392
in Bangladesh through her parents, who were both Bangladeshi by birth.

00:11:02.692 --> 00:11:08.422
But Bangladesh has rejected her outright, saying that she has no right to

00:11:08.422 --> 00:11:13.642
Bangladeshi citizenship, and if she attempted to enter the country, she would face

00:11:13.642 --> 00:11:18.632
the death penalty, due to the country’s zero-tolerance policy towards terrorism.

00:11:19.592 --> 00:11:23.892
Bangladesh says it has nothing to do with her; she was born in Britain,

00:11:24.242 --> 00:11:29.462
it’s where she lived her entire life before going to Syria, she had British

00:11:29.492 --> 00:11:34.092
citizenship, it has no interest in her and she is Britain’s problem.

00:11:35.322 --> 00:11:39.342
In fact, she had even claimed that she was looking into obtaining Dutch

00:11:39.472 --> 00:11:44.032
citizenship through her husband, an ISIS fighter but technically a

00:11:44.072 --> 00:11:49.062
Dutch citizen, but the Dutch government has basically said “no way”.

00:11:50.382 --> 00:11:55.822
Clearly, for Shamima Begum, she is in this strange diplomatic vacuum,

00:11:56.422 --> 00:12:01.192
rejected by her country of birth, rejected by both countries that she could

00:12:01.202 --> 00:12:05.982
have some claim to be a citizen of, and stuck in a Syrian refugee camp.

00:12:07.462 --> 00:12:12.672
And, to take the other side of the argument for a moment, this is deeply unfair.

00:12:13.772 --> 00:12:18.122
Citizenship is a fundamental human right, not a privilege to

00:12:18.122 --> 00:12:22.242
be withdrawn, and Britain needs to take responsibility for her.

00:12:23.132 --> 00:12:26.672
She was British, she was radicalised in Britain.

00:12:27.532 --> 00:12:33.862
Leaving her to rot in a Syrian refugee camp is deeply unfair and sets a dangerous

00:12:33.892 --> 00:12:38.672
precedent, allowing the government to revoke citizenship based on certain criteria.

00:12:39.642 --> 00:12:42.372
What’s more, she was 15 when she left.

00:12:43.182 --> 00:12:45.252
Legally, she was still a child.

00:12:46.002 --> 00:12:47.832
We all make mistakes when we’re 15.

00:12:48.922 --> 00:12:52.852
Sure, we don’t all join the Islamic State, but she was

00:12:52.852 --> 00:12:56.252
a child and this should be taken into consideration.

00:12:57.682 --> 00:13:04.492
As a child, should the fault be put squarely on her, or on those who groomed or radicalised her?

00:13:05.922 --> 00:13:09.522
Yes, she made a mistake, and yes, it was a really bad mistake.

00:13:10.372 --> 00:13:15.232
But once she had made the decision to get on that plane to Turkey, and then get

00:13:15.232 --> 00:13:19.672
smuggled over the border, there was nothing more that she could have done to get out.

00:13:20.732 --> 00:13:26.122
She couldn’t really have run away, as that would have meant risking her life; if she'd

00:13:26.182 --> 00:13:31.932
been caught, she would undoubtedly have been put in prison, tortured and perhaps executed.

00:13:33.032 --> 00:13:39.212
Yes, she was there for 4 years, but she barely left the home, she wasn’t fighting on the frontlines.

00:13:39.982 --> 00:13:41.802
Or at least, she says she wasn’t.

00:13:43.382 --> 00:13:45.912
And what’s more, she suffered terribly.

00:13:46.712 --> 00:13:51.232
She fell pregnant five times, lost two babies during the

00:13:51.232 --> 00:13:55.992
pregnancies, and all three of her surviving children died.

00:13:57.572 --> 00:14:02.992
She was abused by her husband, so she says, she saw her friends killed, she has already

00:14:02.992 --> 00:14:09.122
experienced more than enough heartbreak and anguish, and she is still only in her early 20s.

00:14:09.992 --> 00:14:13.982
Bring her back to Britain to face justice here, some people say.

00:14:15.292 --> 00:14:20.992
Of course, she should pay for her actions, but it is much better to bring her back to her

00:14:21.002 --> 00:14:26.522
home country to face trial rather than leave her in a refugee camp with hundreds of other

00:14:26.532 --> 00:14:32.832
former ISIS members, where she will remain as radical as ever, and might easily escape.

00:14:34.212 --> 00:14:39.732
In other words, perhaps counterintuitively, she poses a greater threat to

00:14:39.742 --> 00:14:45.032
Britain in an insecure refugee camp in Syria than she would safely behind bars

00:14:45.222 --> 00:14:49.612
in a British prison or under the careful watch of the police back in London.

00:14:51.112 --> 00:14:56.352
Whatever side you are more inclined to take, it's undeniable is Shamima Begum doesn’t

00:14:56.352 --> 00:15:00.432
seem to be doing herself any favours through the TV interviews that she's given.

00:15:01.782 --> 00:15:07.492
Especially during the early interviews, from 2019, she showed no remorse

00:15:07.642 --> 00:15:12.642
whatsoever and continued to show sympathy for ISIS's values and beliefs.

00:15:14.242 --> 00:15:17.702
She even sort of boasted that she'd seen beheaded

00:15:17.762 --> 00:15:21.472
heads in the bin, the severed heads of enemy fighters.

00:15:22.662 --> 00:15:26.762
And when the journalist asked her what that felt like, she said

00:15:26.772 --> 00:15:29.982
that it didn’t “faze her at all”, she wasn’t bothered by it

00:15:31.519 --> 00:15:37.631
Perhaps this just shows naivety, that she grossly misunderstood what might happen,

00:15:38.091 --> 00:15:43.911
and simply assumed that she could click her fingers and come “home” to Britain, and

00:15:44.131 --> 00:15:48.021
she got a nasty shock when she discovered that it was not going to be easy at all.

00:15:49.611 --> 00:15:56.181
Now, we've been speaking only about Shamima Begum today, but clearly she is just one example.

00:15:56.671 --> 00:16:00.381
Thousands of people left their European homes to join the

00:16:00.381 --> 00:16:04.971
Islamic State, and many are now holed up in refugee camps.

00:16:05.961 --> 00:16:07.251
What should happen to them?

00:16:08.611 --> 00:16:12.591
Of course, nobody is suggesting that they receive some kind of hero’s

00:16:12.591 --> 00:16:17.241
welcome, but should they be deprived of their citizenship and left in

00:16:17.311 --> 00:16:21.691
permanent exile or should they be returned to their country of origin?

00:16:23.101 --> 00:16:26.811
